<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - Natural Resource Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/natres.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/i.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>n the greater scheme of things, but particularly in the Canadian equity markets, I believe that the natural resource sector will eventually be hailed as the darling of the investment world. That is somewhere ahead of us of course, but we don't want to wait and be buying the "darlings," do we? We want to be <i>selling</i> the "darlings" to those who don't know any better.<p>Again, the TSE 100 Resource Index is giving a solid performance. Gradually, the various natural resources sectors are combining to provide a more equal share of market power. If you recall, at the end of August I told you about a technical breakout in the Oil and Gas sector, projecting a 28% move to 6800 pt. We are only a couple of percent short of this initial target and may see higher values yet. The TSE Metals index is almost at 5800 pt. On a breakout <i>above </i>5800, the Metals Index projects a move to 6600 or 15% gain. During the Spring, I marked The Paper and Forest Products chart with the message "cycle lows." Since then a slow but steady continuing investment recovery has helped natural resource fund portfolios. So what's left out from this happy little picture? Gold.<p>London Gold bullion prices have now sagged down through my Stop point and I have to rate bullion as a Sell. The TSE Gold Index has fared better. TSE Gold Index,  having made three intermediate term lows in the past year, has each low higher than the previous, indicating a modest uptrend. While there may be a number of reasons for this behaviour, the best one is the split personality of the Canadian gold sector. If you invest in a company engaged in <i>exploration,</i> you have probably made money. If your funds are in a gold <i>processing</i> company, lower bullion prices will have reduced profitability and share prices. </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2><br><img src="../images/charts.gif" width=80 height=15><font face="Arial" size=-1><hr noshade color=#297b63></center>Note: Charts are<br>designed for full<br>screen viewing.<p><center><b><a href="charts/tse100re.gif">TSE Resource<p></a><a href="charts/londongo.gif">London Gold<p></a><a href="charts/tsegold.gif">TSE Gold<p></a><a href="charts/tseoilan.gif">TSE Oil/Gas<p></a><a href="charts/tsemetal.gif">TSE Metal<p></a><a href="charts/tsepaper.gif">TSE Paper<p></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade color=#297b63><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td align=center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="canada.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=55 height=16 border=0 align=left></a><a href="bonds.html"><img src="../images/next.gif" width=51 height=16 border=0 align=right></a><a href="index.html#contents"><img src="../images/contents.gif" width=106 height=16 border=0></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><center><address><font size=-1><a href="../copyright.html">Copyright and Disclaimer</a></center><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade><center><address><font size=-1><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left>Site design by <a href="http://www.compulinks.com">CompuLink Services</a>.<br><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left>Contact <a hre