<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - International Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/inter.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><img src="../letters/w.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1><font size=-1 face=Arial><b>orld markets, as evidenced by the Dow Jones World Average and the Morgan Stanley E.A.FE, continue to advance in an orderly uptrend</b>. The DJ World Index is at new highs and the widely followed E.A.FE is just about to break out into new highs. This action could see a sharp move ahead for investors holding good quality diversified International mutual funds.<p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/e.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>UROPE. Last month I advocated caution for European investment funds on the grounds that the Morgan Stanley Europe Index was overbought. While this market has gone sideways since then, it's really too soon to make any further recommendations. <b>Hold'em if you've got 'em, but don't add to your position just yet.<p></b><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/a.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>SIA. <b>It's still a NO to Japanese funds</b>. I've made a slight adjustment to the long term multi-year price ceiling to get a better fit, but the result is still the same. Wait for 22,800 on the Nikkei to get a buy signal. <b>Hong Kong is steaming towards a price target of 14900 points and Singapore is also moving higher</b>. A quick scan of several Asian-based Closed End funds supports the idea that Asian markets are moving higher. Again, my most favoured fund for this situation continues to be Fidelity's Far East Fund.<p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/l.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>ATIN AMERICA. The economists are forever saying that things are improving in Latin America. I also saw a recent Globe and mail article about money managers taking a serious view of Latin opportunities. Unfortunately, that is not showing up too well in the performance of Canadian mutual funds. Over the past month, Canadian based Latin funds are near bottom on my International funds performance list. <b>While no Latin funds showed any  losses, better investment opportunities do exist elsewhere. </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2><br><img src="../images/charts.gif" width=80 height=15><font face="Arial" size=-1><hr noshade color=#297b63></center>Note: Charts are<br>designed for full<br>screen viewing.<p><center><b><a href="charts/europe.gif">Europe<p></a><a href="charts/eafe.gif">E. A. FE<p></a><a href="charts/djworld.gif">DJ World<p></a><a href="charts/tokyonik.gif">Tokyo<p></a><a href="charts/hongkong.gif">Hong Kong<p></a><a href="charts/mexicanb.gif">Mexican Bolsa<p></a><a href="charts/singapor.gif">Singapore<p></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade color=#297b63><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td align=center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="us.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=55 height=16 border=0 align=left></a><a href="asset.html"><img src="../images/next.gif" width=51 height=16 border=0 align=right></a><a href="index.html#contents"><img src="../images/contents.gif" width=106 height=16 border=0></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><center><address><font size=-1><a href="../copyright.html">Copyright and Disclaimer</a></center><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade><center><address><font size=-1><img src="../images/spacer.gi