<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - US Equity Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/us.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><font color=#215a42> <i>"You can fool too many of the people too much of the time</i>"  -James Thurber</font><p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/a.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>hh Politics, Politics... The US Presidential Elections are over, with incumbent President Clinton winning by a substantial margin. The US markets have rocketed in the last couple of days, showing that the World's investors have embraced a Democrat President and a Republican Congress, the first re-elected Republican Congress since 1930. Unfortunately, voter turn out was the lowest in 72 years, speaking volumes for the perceived qualities of the candidates. 55% of polled voters said that they did not consider Mr. Clinton to be "trustworthy."<p>In late July, I directed you to two "market reversal day" signals and commented that the market was oversold and ripe for a multi-month rally. Well, we're here. Now that many more investors now believe that it's a great market, it's time to get cagey, not complacent. Enjoy the rally while we've got it, <i>the trend is your friend</i>, but remember, the honeymoon always ends sometime.<p>My expectations from four months ago were for better performance from biotechnology and Nasdaq high tech stocks. Unfortunately, some Biotech stocks have lagged a bit, but high tech., plus the NYA, S&P 500 and the blue chip Dow Jones Industrial Average have done equally well since. The Dow has reached into my target zone of 6200-6400 points mentioned in the September letter, but as said then, it may go higher. I wish that I had the skill to tell you when to bail out. Personally, I'm going to stay with the trend for as long as I dare. US stock market historian Yale Hirsch says that a re-elected President usually spells trouble for the stock market, especially if the markets were very strong before the Presidential Election. Yale says that after re-election the markets have fallen by an average of 11% with the worst drops down to about 20%. exception and had a bull market to support him? Ronald Reagan!!<p> </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2><br><img src="../images/charts.gif" width=80 height=15><font face="Arial" size=-1><hr noshade color=#297b63></center>Note: Charts are<br>designed for full<br>screen viewing.<p><center><b><a href="charts/dowjones.gif">Dow Jones<p></a><a href="charts/nasdaq.gif">NASDAQ<p></a><a href="charts/cboebiot.gif">CBOE Biotech<p></a><a href="charts/sp500.gif">S & P 500<p></a><a href="charts/nycompos.gif">N.Y. Composite<p></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade color=#297b63><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td align=center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="bonds.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=55 height=16 border=0 align=left></a><a href="inter.html"><img src="../images/next.gif" width=51 height=16 border=0 align=right></a><a href="index.html#contents"><img src="../images/contents.gif" width=106 height=16 border=0></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><center><address><font size=-1><a href="../copyright.html">Copyright and Disclaimer</a></center><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade><center><address><font size=-1><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left>Site design by <a href="http://www.compulinks.