<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - International Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/inter.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/w.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1><b>orld markets continue to trend upwards</b>, spurred by falling interest rates and positive action from the US markets. Continue to buy broadly based International funds selected from the "Best Funds List."<p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/e.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>UROPE. The <b>Morgan Stanley Europe Index is still trending higher, but is becoming</b> <b>overbought.</b> All the major European Stock Exchanges are still in good shape so I'll elect to stay with European funds for this month. It's probably time to <b>start being cautious as far</b> <b>as adding lots of new money to the pot</b>. It will be better to wait for a correction before investing more assets in Europe.<p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/a.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>SIA. <b>Still "NO" for Japan, I'm sorry to say</b>. How many months have I been writing those few words? The buy point is still 22,800 pts on the Nikkei. THEN you can fill your boots with the stuff. Just to be sure of my opinion, I looked at the performance of six good Canadian mutual funds invested in Japan. You should be glad you don't own them.<p>The Hong Kong markets are doing well and have just climbed above the all time highs at about 1200+.<b> A move to 1490 is now possible.</b> Given these conditions, a good choice of fund is <b>Fidelity Far East Fund. </b>I have recommended this one before. Fidelity's biggest holding is in Hong Kong (60+% of portfolio) and the fund owns no Japanese stocks.<p><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/l.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>ATIN FUNDS. <i>Siesta</i> prevails with the Latin funds. My favourite Latin funds are making infinitesimally modest gains, but are not a screaming buy at this time. If you bought on my recommendation a few months ago you should have a small profit. I recommend holding. If you are waiting, keep waiting for some strong price action. </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2><br><img src="../images/charts.gif" width=80 height=15><font face="Arial" size=-1><hr noshade color=#297b63></center>Note: Charts are<br>designed for full<br>screen viewing.<p><center><b><a href="charts/europe.gif">Europe<p></a><a href="charts/eafe.gif">E. A. FE<p></a><a href="charts/djworld.gif">DJ World<p></a><a href="charts/tokyo.gif">Tokyo<p></a><a href="charts/hongkong.gif">Hong Kong<p></a><a href="charts/mexicanb.gif">Mexican Bolsa<p></a><a href="charts/usvsmexp.gif">US $ vs Mex.<p></a><a href="charts/singapor.gif">Singapore<p></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade color=#297b63><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td align=center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="us.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=55 height=16 border=0 align=left></a><a href="asset.html"><img src="../images/next.gif" width=51 height=16 border=0 align=right></a><a href="index.html#contents"><img src="../images/contents.gif" width=106 height=16 border=0></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><center><address><font size=-1><a href="../copyright.html">Copyright and Disclaimer</a></center><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade><center><address><font size=-1><img src="../images/spacer