<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - Bond Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/bonds.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/t.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>he rate of <i>decline</i> in bond prices in both the US and Canada continues to slow. However, prices haven't clearly turned the corner into an uptrend yet. The political and economic messages are still mixed. Mr. Greenspan has had the opportunity to hike US interest rates, but appears to be staying true to the Presidential Election Cycle and avoiding a rate increase until after the November elections. Heaven help us in early 1997 when Bill Clinton is re-elected and US monetary policy will need to be cleaned up. Mr. Greenspan was speaking to Congress last week and mentioned concerns about rising wage inflation. As I advised last month, rising wages are one of the most important contributors to price inflation. On the other side of the coin, the CRB Index, our harbinger of consumer price inflation, has dropped like a rock over the past month. It looks to me as if the CRB commodity inflation scare is over for a while.<p>In the US I continue to watch 7.0% to 7.5% yield on longer term bonds. Yields exceeding 7.5% may be disastrous for the markets. <b>In Canada, I have recommended buying bonds and bond funds and I am using $106.00 on Government of Canada 9% bonds of 2011 as a Stop point. A move in bond prices above $111.00 on a weekly basis will point to a new bond rally. </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=