<html><head><title>The Informed Investor Newsletter - Bond Funds</title></head><body background="../images/tile.gif" bgcolor=#ffffff link=#297b63 vlink=#297b63 alink=#31ad84><a href="../index.html"><img src="../images/home.gif" width=55 height=16 align=right border=0 alt="Home" vspace=5 hspace=5></a>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <img src="../titles/bonds.gif"><p><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6><tr><td><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2></td><td><font size=-1 face=Arial><img src="../letters/s.gif" align=left vspace=1 hspace=1>ince our last issue, we have had a fairly strong rally on the Canadian side of the bond market, with the US side moving a little more sedately. I believe that it's time to get back into the bond market, buying quality bond funds and buying bonds to hold for maturity. Look closely at the action of past bond selloffs on the Government of Canada bonds of 2011. You can see that when the bond market corrects it will break below the trend-smoothing 30 week moving average. The bonds then start a strong recovery. That should be the way things go this time. Our low point in late April was $106.00. We will use that as our Stop Out point in case I am being a little too quick off the mark.<p>In the US, the bond markets have been mixed in the past few weeks. The Fed. stance seems to be to avoid changing interest rates going into the Presidential Elections. This accommodates Mr. Clinton, who is also trying to ensure smooth sailing by pushing hard to get Democrat Fed. nominee's approved quickly. Some Fed. officials are getting a little concerned that rising wage demands may become an inflationary factor and that rising commodities prices will be more than a short term phenomenon. Overall economic factors remain positive. Productivity for US workers grew by 2.6% for the first quarter. America claims the most productive workers in the world based on these figures, and worker efficiency is an essential component to generating fast growth without increases in inflation. Unemployment is down to 5.5% and retail sales are slightly lower.<p>The CRB Index, our harbinger of consumer inflation got as high as 264.00 and has gone into a minor correction phase. The long term trend is still heading up. I am still betting on 272.00+ as an upside target. </td><td> &nbsp</td><td background="../images/tbltile.gif" bgcolor=#c6d6c6 valign=top><center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2><br><img src="../images/charts.gif" width=80 height=15><font face="Arial" size=-1><hr noshade color=#297b63></center>Note: Charts are<br>designed for full<br>screen viewing.<p><center><b><a href="charts/10yrustb.gif">10 Yr. US T-Bonds<p></a><a href="charts/crbindex.gif">CRB Index<p></a><a href="charts/canbonds.gif">Can. Bonds<p></a><a href="charts/usvscdn.gif">US $ vs Cdn.<p></a><a href="charts/usvsgerm.gif">US $ vs Germ.<p></a><a href="charts/usvsjapy.gif">US $ vs Yen<p></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade color=#297b63><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td align=center><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="mutual.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=55 height=16 border=0 align=left></a><a href="ironlady.html"><img src="../images/next.gif" width=51 height=16 border=0 align=right></a><a href="index.html#contents"><img src="../images/contents.gif" width=106 height=16 border=0></a></td></tr></table><p><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><center><address><font size=-1><a href="../copyright.html">Copyright and Disclaimer</a></center><p><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><hr noshade><center><address><font size=-1><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left>Site design by <a href="http://www.compulinks.com">CompuLink Services</a>.<br><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left>Contact <a href="mailto:webmaster@compulinks.com">webmaster@compulinks.com</a> with comments.<br><img src="../images/spacer.gif" width=95 height=2 align=left><a href="http://www.compulinks.com"><img src="../images/smllogo.gif" width=171 height=26 border=0 vspace=5 alt="CompuLink Services"></a></address></font><p><font color=#ffffff>23</center></body></html>
